{{Distinguish|Thomas Beale}}
'''Thomas Chay Beale''' (13 December 1805 – 3 November 1857) was a Scottish merchant and diplomat operating in the [[Far East]] during the 19th century. He was a Chevalier of the [[Legion of Honor]] and of the Portuguese Order of Christ.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Deaths|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=40BDAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA225&dq=Thomas+Chay+Beale|accessdate=27 May 2018|journal=The Gentleman's Magazine|publisher=R. Newton|date=February 1858|page=225|language=en}}</ref>

==Biography==
Chay Beale was a nephew of opium trader and merchant [[Daniel Beale]] and his brother [[Thomas Beale]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Le Pichon|first1=Alain|title=China Trade and Empire: Jardine, Matheson & Co. and the Origins of British Rule in Hong Kong, 1827-1843|date=2006|publisher=OUP/British Academy|isbn=9780197263372|page=93|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0ql7CqEV6d4C&pg=PA93&dq=Thomas+Chay+Beale|accessdate=27 May 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref name="OPC">{{Cite web|url=http://gwulo.com/sites/gwulo.com/.../Gwulo-Macau-Old-Protestant-Cemetery.pdf|title=Old Protestant Cemetery in Macau|accessdate=May 31, 2011}}{{Dead link|date=June 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}</ref> As early as 1826, he was a partner in the trading firm of [[Hollingworth Magniac|Magniac & Co.]] in [[Canton (Guangzhou)|Canton]], China. In the 1830s he left Magniacs and operated on his own until 1845 when he established the [[Shanghai]] based agency house of Dent, Beale & Co. with [[Lancelot Dent]]. By 1851, Beale was Portuguese Consul and Dutch Vice Counsel in the city.<ref>Cranmer-Byng J.L. and Ride, Lindsay T., ''Journal of Occurrences at Canton 1839'' [sic] in Journal of the Royal Asiatic Society Hong Kong Branch; Vol. 4 (1964) p. 37</ref>

He is buried in the Shantung Road Cemetery in [[Shanghai]] and there is a memorial to him in the church of St. Mary the Virgin in [[Brettenham, Suffolk]].

